This paper is primarily focused on generative models for natural images and videos, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) also suggests a strong likelihood of the paper belonging to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper leverages a computationally efficient decomposition of its discriminator, which could potentially fall under the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. The evaluation of the model on related tasks such as video synthesis and prediction also suggests a possible fit for the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the use of complex datasets such as Kinetics-600 and UCF-101 could potentially place the paper under the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category.
